		<li class="alt" id="comment-47993">
			<h4 class="comments-author"><a href="http://dlowe-wfh.blogspot.com">David Lowe</a> Says:</h4>
			<small class="comments-metadata"><a href="#comment-47993" title="">August 19th, 2010 at 02:33 PM</a></small>
			<p class="comments-entry"><p>I have used this to recover lost work. It&#8217;s a good trick.</p>


	<p>I&#8217;d add this advice, though: make sure you write your output to a different partition than the one you&#8217;re trying to recover from, or you risk that your output reuses some of the very blocks you&#8217;re after!</p></p>
		</li>
  
		<li class="" id="comment-47994">
			<h4 class="comments-author"><a href="http://www.mosquito.pro.br">Paulo Eduardo Neves</a> Says:</h4>
			<small class="comments-metadata"><a href="#comment-47994" title="">August 19th, 2010 at 02:52 PM</a></small>
			<p class="comments-entry"><p>Great tip! You can simplify your command with the -C flag. Use grep -C 201 to get 100 lines above and 100 lines below the matched line. Thanks</p></p>
		</li>
  
		<li class="alt" id="comment-47995">
			<h4 class="comments-author"><span>Anon</span> Says:</h4>
			<small class="comments-metadata"><a href="#comment-47995" title="">August 19th, 2010 at 02:57 PM</a></small>
			<p class="comments-entry"><p>There are some decent &#8220;data carvers&#8221; out there (<a href="http://www.cgsecurity.org/wiki/TestDisk">testdisk</a> and <a href="http://www.cgsecurity.org/wiki/PhotoRec">photorec</a> seem to be the famous open source ones) but nothing is going to beat really good and regular backups (which are tested!).</p></p>
		</li>
  
		<li class="" id="comment-47996">
